'I'he Pontifical of Lacy Bishop of Exeter, circa 1420. now in the Library of the Dean and Chapter of Exeter.

This was published by the late Mr Ralph Barnes in 1847. and can still be had, 1 believe, at Stewart’s, King William Street, Strand. ,

Lacy was consecrated Bishop of Hereford in 1417 and translated to Exeter in 1420.

The proof of ownership is given ou the 2nd folio; “ Hunc Librum Pontificalem dederunt executores bonae memoriae Edmundi Lacy nuper dum vixit Exoniensis Episcopi, de bonis

ejusdem Ecclesiae cathedralis Exoniensis ibidem remansurum &c.” ⁴

Bodleian Library‚ MS. Tanner 5. saec. xiv. ineunt.

This is endorsed by a late hand, as a Sarum Pontifical, but there is no evidence whatever that it belonged to a Bishop of Salisbury. It is almost identical in all the strictly Pontifical Offices with Lacy’s, just described, but ⁴it has neither the Coronation Office nor the Office for consecration of Chrism secundum Usum Sarum. Still, the two MSS did not belong to successive holders of the same See, as is plain from the considerable variations between2them in the Manual OfficeS, especially those for Baptism and Matrimony.

British Museum, additional MSS. 6157. saec. xv.

This fragment consisting of 146 leaves, is exceedingly similar inwriting to Archbishop Ghichele's Pontifical and is also for an Archbishop of Canterbury. Its contents are nearly identical with the very peculiar Offices in Archbishop Ohichele’s book, as far as they go.
